(a) Substantives

1. ABSTRACT NOUNs: These are very common in Octavius. Abstraot ideas are personified and made subj. of the verb, eg. intentio mentis resedit (1. 5); ferociente victoria (6. 2); ef. 5. 113 7. 2; 8. 2; 9. 33 31. 3, eto.; Cio. uses the abstraet sometimes for the concrete, but the tendenoy in class. Lat. is markedly in favour of the latter.

In class. Lat. the plur. of the abstraet subst. is used where Eng. has sing„ to denote an action repeated (eg. in mare iaculationibus 2. 3) or to denote that a quality or action is common to several persons or things (eg. caedibus sacerdotum 23. 1). In Imper. Lat. this use is less restricted, eg. 1. 53 3. 3; 12. 6; 11. 4; 16. 5; 23. 4, eto.
